Italy DCP data on COVID-19

Matteo Castagna

30 March, 2020 - 17:32

[VERY DRAFT]

An attempt is being made to make sense of the important dataset published daily by the Italian DPC1. It is updated (daily, usually around 17:30 GMT) on GitHub at the following address https://github.com/pcm-dpc/COVID-19.

Data are published both at a County (Provincie) and Region (Regioni) level; the latter offers more information in terms of number of fields. At County level only the “infections” number is given.

This job is divided in two parts:

  1. Figuring out the number of actual infected. It is immediately obvious that the “tested positive” number being supplied is not correct once the death-rate and a reasonable lead time to death since detection are accounted for. Starting from a reasonable hypothesis on the death-rate and that lead time, an actual number of infected can be computed.
  2. Predicting the number of deaths for each day/Region over the following two weeks. This is a more challenging and crucial portion of the job: it involves considering methods based on machine learning, optimizing the relevant parameter with cross-validation techniques and then providing a new dataset (forward-looking) and run the optimized model on them. The infected multiplier computed in the first part is used to create the “infected” variable from the reported ones.

Assuming this is done correctly (fairly safe, as the cause of death is provided following the OMS protocol), and given a relatively tight range of the death rate2 these are then the numbers guiding the entire work.

While an estimate of the percentage of population actually infected is calculated by applying a very simple model, the number of predicted deaths is obtained via machine learning using the gradient boosting machine algorithm to identify the correct model (GBM)3.

GBM seems to offer encouraging results at cross validation level and the predicted path for a selected number of regions is charted at the end4.

1 The “true” infected percentage of population

1.2 Calculating the infected from the daily number of deceased

dthRateHp <- 0.035
lag <- 16

This initial model assumes the most reliable data is provided by the number of deaths at each date/region. Assuming a death-rate of 3.5% and a lag between the detected infection and the actual death of 16 days, for each date/region, you can derive the actual number of infected people over the total population.

\[ \text{Infected*}_{t,R} = \frac {dead_{t+lag,R}}{deathRate}\]

\[ \text{Multiplier}_{t,R} = \frac{\text{Infected*}_{t,R}}{\text{Officially Infected}_{t,R}}\] [R is the index for the Region, t is the ID of a specific date]

This can be charted as follows:

### Multipliers set

MultSet <- dfReg %>%
  arrange(data) %>%
  group_by(Regione) %>%
  mutate(leadDead = lead(deceduti, lag),
         hpCasi = leadDead/dthRateHp,
         hpCasiOnCasi = hpCasi/totale_casi) %>%
  filter(!is.infinite(hpCasiOnCasi), !is.na(hpCasiOnCasi), !is.nan(hpCasiOnCasi),
         data > as.Date("2020-02-27")) %>%
  ungroup()

### Multipliers chart

MultSet %>%  
  ggplot(aes(x= data, y = hpCasiOnCasi, color = Regione)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Infected multiplier by date/region",
       subtitle = paste0("Death rate: ", format(dthRateHp* 100), "%, lag: ", lag, " days"),
       caption = paste("SOURCE: DPC data as of", format(maxDateTime, "%d-%h %H:%M")),
       x= "",
       y = "Multiplier")

A dataset is built5 and the results projected for the last available date.

The logical jump made is: the Multiplier for (t,R) is a good proxy for the multiplier as of (t+lag,R). Without that assumption we would be always 16 days behind.

Effectively we assume:

\[\text{Multiplier}_{max(t)} = \frac{\text{Infected*}_{max(t-lag),R}}{\text{Officially Infected}_{max(t),R}}\]

Let’s consider Lombardia: the estimated percentage of the infected population is currently equal to % while the official numbers point to only %.

The “multiplier”, based on the number of deaths, for 14-Mar (T-16) is 16.7.

It’s interesting to note the effect of the different focus on testing. Veneto is considered the region at the forefront of the policy “test as much as you can”. As a result its multiplier is the lowest among the most affected areas.

2 Charting the daily deaths path

2.1 Tree-based model

This is where machine learning (ie, passing data/outcomes and getting the rules, instead of processing the data/rules to get the outcome) is used.

The model implemented is the Generalized Boosted Regression Model (GBM)

This is a bit of a “black-box” style algorithm which is very useful for prediction7 and somewhat useful for inference.

lastMultSet <- lastMultSet %>%
  rename(Region = Regione)

modelSet <- dfReg %>%
  select(data, 
         ricov = ricoverati_con_sintomi, ICU = terapia_intensiva,
         homeBound = isolamento_domiciliare, currentPositives = Positivi,
         discharged = dimessi_guariti, dead = deceduti, totalInfected = totale_casi,
         tests = tamponi, Region = Regione, Pop = census, RegSize = size,
         RegAvgDens = density, MainArea = class) %>%
  left_join(lastMultSet, by  = "Region") %>%
  mutate(MainArea = as.factor(MainArea),
         Region = as.factor(Region),
         days = as.numeric(data-min(data)),
         infected = totalInfected * hpCasiOnCasi) %>%  ### Infected adjusted by the multiplier
  select(-c(data, hpCasiOnCasi)) %>%
  arrange(days) %>%
  group_by(Region) %>%
  mutate(DDead = dead-lag(dead)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(!is.na(DDead)) %>%
  select(-c(currentPositives, ricov, totalInfected, dead))

is.fact <- sapply(modelSet, is.factor)
is.num <- sapply(modelSet, is.numeric)

Variables: 2 are factors and 10 are numeric.

dependentVariable <- "DDead"

depVar <- modelSet[, dependentVariable]
num.var <- modelSet[, !(names(modelSet) %in% dependentVariable) & is.num]
fact.var <- modelSet[, is.fact]

correlation <- cor(num.var)

highCorr <- findCorrelation(correlation, cutoff = .80)
highCorrNames <- names(num.var[, highCorr])

The objective is to fit the daily change in the deaths number (DDead variable).

corrplot(correlation, type= "lower", order = "hclust")

Highly correlated variables are ICU,homeBound,infected. Ideally you would get rid of them to avoid multicollinearity. Given it’s tree-based model it doesn’t really matter.

Transforming factors into dummy variable (with all cases - tree model)

trnsFact <- dummyVars(~., data=fact.var, fullRank = F)
factData <- predict(trnsFact, fact.var)

fullSet_pp <- cbind(factData, num.var, depVar)

Cross-validation and the optimization of the hyper-parameters of the GBM algorithm has been done separately as it requires substantial run-time.

set.seed(1)
inTraining <- createDataPartition(fullSet_pp[, dependentVariable], p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
train <- fullSet_pp[inTraining,]
test <- fullSet_pp[-inTraining,]

load("optHpars.Rda")

gbm.fit.final <- gbm(
  formula = DDead ~ .,
  distribution = "gaussian",
  data = train,
  n.trees = optHpars$optimal_trees,
  interaction.depth = optHpars$interaction.depth,
  shrinkage = optHpars$shrinkage,
  n.minobsinnode = optHpars$n.minobsinnode,
  bag.fraction = optHpars$bag.fraction, 
  train.fraction = 1,
  n.cores = NULL, 
  verbose = FALSE
)  

RMSEtrn <- caret::RMSE(train[, dependentVariable],
                       predict(gbm.fit.final, n.trees = optHpars$optimal_trees))
RMSEtst <- caret::RMSE(test[, dependentVariable],
                       predict(gbm.fit.final, n.trees = optHpars$optimal_trees, test))

RMSE train: 0.6 and RMSE test: 23

Using the optimized parameters the final model is then created using the entire dataset.

show(chart)

Given the nature of the algorithm it is not possible to provide a classical beta to the different independent variables. It is possible though charting the partial effect on the dependent variable of the values of a single independent one.

gbm.fit.final %>%
  pdp::partial(pred.var = "ICU", n.trees = optHpars$optimal_trees, grid.resolution = 100) %>%
  autoplot(rug = TRUE, train = fullSet_pp) +
  theme_bw()

gbm.fit.final %>%
  pdp::partial(pred.var = "discharged", n.trees = optHpars$optimal_trees, grid.resolution = 100) %>%
  autoplot(rug = TRUE, train = fullSet_pp) +
  theme_bw()

plot(fullSet_pp[, dependentVariable], predict(gbm.fit.final, n.trees = optHpars$optimal_trees), 
     main = "Actual/Fitted DDead (45deg line)",
     xlab = "Actual", ylab = "Fitted")
abline(0,1, col = "red")

2.2 Predicting the deaths path

The output from the GBM model will be used. Two extra weeks will be added assuming the same path currently experienced for the relevant variables.

maxDay = max(fullSet_pp$days)
newDays <- seq(maxDay + 1, maxDay + 15, by = 1)

2.2.1 Creating the independent variables dataset

The four independent variable which need to have forward values are:

  • Number of infected in ICU
  • Number of infected (computed as: multiplier times officially-reported)
  • Number of infected home-bound
  • Number of tests executed
  • Number of infected discharged

The historical log values of the four variable is charted by Region.

vars <- modelSet %>%
  select(Region, ICU, homeBound, discharged, tests, days, infected) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(ICU, homeBound, discharged, tests, infected)) %>%
  filter(value != 0) %>%
  mutate(value = log(value)) %>%
  as.data.frame()

vars %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= days, y  = value, color = name)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~Region, ncol = 4) + 
  theme_bw() +
  scale_color_discrete("") +
  theme(legend.position="bottom") +
  labs(y = "log(values)",
       x = paste("Days since", format(min(dfReg$data), "%d-%h")))

A quadratic regression on their log values seems a reasonable option. For each region/variable a new set of independent variables is then built8.

polyICU <- 2
polyDIS <- 2
polyHOM <- 1
polyTES <- 2
polyINF <- 2


if(exists("fwdDays")) rm(fwdDays)

for(Reg in setdiff(unique(vars$Region), "Basilicata")){
  for(Var in unique(vars$name)) {
    thisModel <- lm(value ~ poly(days, switch(Var,
                                              ICU = polyICU,
                                              tests = polyTES,
                                              discharged = polyDIS,
                                              homeBound = polyHOM,
                                              infected = polyINF)),
                    data = vars[vars$Region == Reg &
                                  vars$name == Var,])

    thisDf <- data.frame(days = newDays,
                         name = Var,
                         values = exp(predict(thisModel, newdata = data.frame(days = newDays))),
                         Region = Reg,
                         RegAvgDens = popPerReg$density[popPerReg$Regione == Reg],
                         Pop = popPerReg$census[popPerReg$Regione == Reg],
                         RegSize = popPerReg$size[popPerReg$Regione == Reg],
                         class = as.factor(regSet$class[gsub(" |'", "",regSet$Regione) == Reg]))
    
    fwdDays <- if(exists("fwdDays")) rbind(fwdDays, thisDf) else  thisDf
  }
}

rm(Var, Reg, thisDf, thisModel)

fwdDays <- fwdDays %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = name, values_from = values) %>%
  rename(MainArea = class)

trnsFact <- dummyVars(~Region + MainArea, data=fwdDays, fullRank = F)
factData <- predict(trnsFact, fwdDays)

fwdDays <- cbind(fwdDays, factData) %>%
  mutate(Region.Basilicata = 0) %>%
  select(-c(MainArea))
pastData <- modelSet[, c("days", "DDead", "Region")] %>%
  mutate(set = "actual")

newdataPnts <- data.frame(days = rep(newDays, length(unique(fwdDays$Region))),
                          DDead = predict(gbm.fit.final, newdata = fwdDays[, names(fwdDays) != "Regione"], 
                                          n.trees = optHpars$optimal_trees),
                          set = "predicted",
                          Region = fwdDays$Region,
                          stringsAsFactors = F)

finalSet <- rbind(pastData, newdataPnts) %>%
  mutate(DDead = ifelse(DDead < 0, 0, DDead))

2.2.2 Predicting the additional deaths/day/region

Using the new independent variables the forward number of additional deaths for each forward day can be predicted and charted at regional level

finalSet %>% ggplot(aes(x = days, y = DDead, linetype = set)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_vline(xintercept =  max(pastData$days), color = "blue", size = 0.1) +
  facet_wrap(~Region, scales = "free_y", nrow = 4) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_linetype_discrete("") +
  theme(legend.position="bottom")+
  labs(title = "GBM model prediction - selected regions",
       subtitle = paste("vertical bar is on", format(maxDateTime, "%d-%h")),
       x = paste("Days since", format(min(dfReg$data), "%d-%h")),
       y = "Death per day")

2.2.3 Cumulative charts

Using regional predictions, the path of the daily death count at national level (summing over the different dates the estimates provided before at regional level) can be built.

finalSet %>%
  group_by(set, days) %>%
  summarise(DDead = sum(DDead)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = days, y = DDead, linetype = set)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_vline(xintercept =  max(pastData$days), color = "blue", size = 0.1) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_linetype_discrete("") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  theme(legend.position="bottom")+
  labs(title = "GBM model prediction - Italy (ex-Basilicata)",
       subtitle = paste("vertical bar is on", format(maxDateTime, "%d-%h")),
       x = paste("Days since", format(min(dfReg$data), "%d-%h")),
       y = "Deaths - per day")

finalSet %>%
  group_by(days) %>%
  summarise(DDead = sum(DDead)) %>%
  mutate(DDeadCum = cumsum(DDead),
         set = ifelse(days >= min(newDays), "predicted", "actual")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = days, y = DDeadCum, linetype = set)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_vline(xintercept =  max(pastData$days), color = "blue", size = 0.1) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_linetype_discrete("") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  theme(legend.position="bottom")+
  labs(title = "GBM model prediction - Italy (ex-Basilicata)",
       subtitle = paste("vertical bar is on", format(maxDateTime, "%d-%h")),
       x = paste("Days since", format(min(dfReg$data), "%d-%h")),
       y = "Deaths - cumulative")
